Relations define the type of connection between two entities in a knowledge graph. It specifies how the property and value in a triple are related. Relations give meaning to the connections between entities, transforming them from isolated data points into a network of meaningful nodes.

In a knowledge graph, data represents interconnected, structured information that forms a web of trust by linking entities through defined relationships. This interconnectedness enables not only easy access to information but also enhances its reliability and verifiability. Each data point can be traced, validated, and contextualized, allowing users to explore connections across a trusted network of knowledge. By organizing data in this way, knowledge graphs empower systems and users to derive insights, make inferences, and discover relationships that may not be obvious in isolated datasets.

Entities are the fundamental building blocks of knowledge graphs, representing real-world objects, people, concepts, or ideas that are identifiable and distinct — such as a person (e.g., Albert Einstein), a place (e.g., Paris), an organization (e.g., NASA), or even an abstract concept (e.g., Relativity).

A triple forms the fundamental unit of a knowledge graph, consisting of three key elements: a subject entity (e.g., Albert Einstein), a property, and the corresponding value of that property. This structure offers a flexible and scalable method for organizing data, enabling knowledge graphs to represent factual information about entities in a standardized format.

A property is something that provides more detailed information about an entity. It defines a specific aspect of an entity, such as its name, date of birth, or any other measurable characteristic with a value attached to the property. Properties enrich the knowledge graph by providing context about the entities it contains.

For example, searching for ‘Artist’ will give you all results for artist, whether that’s a type, an attribute, a role, a topic or anything else the query term ‘Artist’ relates to in the spaces it originates in. Each entity has a unique ID and properties that are relevant to help describe it — like a person's birth date or a city's population — and connects to other entities through [relations](https://www.geobrowser.io/space/08c4f093-7858-4b7c-9b94-b82e448abcff/0915a9f9-1a5a-44aa-902d-fad9166227d1) (e.g., ‘Albert Einstein → Wrote → Theory of Relativity’). Categorized into types such as ‘Person’, ‘City’, or ‘Concept’, entities and their relationships form an interconnected network of information, mirroring real-world knowledge in a structured way.

Entities in knowledge graphs are inherently composable, allowing them to be built from or contain other entities to form complex, interconnected structures. For example, the entity ‘Albert Einstein’ can include content blocks, such as his biography or notable achievements, each represented as separate entities. Similarly, facts about him, like the property ‘Birth place’ and its value ‘Germany’, are also entities connected through relationships. This composability enables a modular and flexible representation, where every piece of information contributes to a dynamic, layered understanding of the whole.

Most types in Geo have a defined schema. A schema in this context is a set of properties associated with a type that are automatically inherited by any entity that type is assigned to. If the schema gets updated to include more inherited properties, those properties are added to any entity that has that type assigned to it. This structure ensures that data across the knowledge graph remains consistent, meaningful, and optimized for efficient querying.

Versioning is the practice of maintaining records of different versions or states of data over time. Each time edits to existing data are published, a new version is created, and previous edits are saved in a history panel. Selecting an entry in this panel opens a full-screen view of the proposal, displaying the edits made and showing who voted to accept or reject those edits. This setup allows for unlimited revisions without losing the original data source.

In a space with public governance, creating a proposal is as simple as making edits to a space, reviewing those edits, adding an edit name and publishing for editor review. In a personal space, any editor can make edits in the same way except there is no review process - edits get published instantly.

Geo leverages the structures of a knowledge graph with [IPFS](https://www.geobrowser.io/space/08c4f093-7858-4b7c-9b94-b82e448abcff/8a39d552-ab1d-4515-b7d1-8647fe4f9111) for decentralized data storage, enabling blockchain-based verifiability along with robust version control and historical access to interconnected data. When edits are submitted to Geo in any one of it’s public spaces, editors participate in a 24-hour voting period to review the proposed edits. If a majority of editors accept the edits, they are published to the blockchain and to the space. If not, the changes are rejected. This system ensures transparency and collaboration while maintaining the integrity of the data.

IPFS is a decenztralized, distributed, peer-to-peer file storage and sharing protocol designed to make the web faster, safer, and more open. Files are stored and accessed directly from multiple nodes, removing the need for central servers and they are identified by their unique cryptographic hash of their content rather than their location. When you access a file, IPFS retrieves it from the closest available node which allows for optimized download speeds and reduces load on individual servers. Finally, IPFS enables version control allowing users to retrieve a specific version of a file - even if it has been updated one or many times.

You may have a collection of personal goals and achievements, music mixes you like, favourite restaurants or places. For example, suppose there’s an entity about Radiohead’s albums in the Music space. You want to create a version of this entity in your own space, with updated text and a new avatar to better suit your perspective. To achieve this, you would duplicate the entity into your space, update the text and cover image, and set the Music space as the source for any data you haven’t modified. This allows you to retain the name, avatar, and type in your space’s version of the entity while reflecting your own changes.
